taxonomicNotes: Jackiewicz (1998) states that there are several problems concerning the nomenclature of the family Lymnaeidae, and that there is probably no other snail group in such taxonomical disarray. Stagnicola has been used as a synonym for Lymnaea by various authors, and as a subgenus of Lymnaea by others (Ponder and Waterhouse 1997, Vinarski 2003, NatureServe 2009). Hovingh (1993) lists this species as Lymnaea (Stagnicola) pilsbryi, whereas NatureServe (2009) name it Stagnicola pilsbryi. Dillon (2009) suggests that Lymnaea pilsbryi is a synonym of Lymnaea humilis, but this is neither supported or denied in other literature. Stagnicola is used by Turgeon et al. (1998) in the most recent list. However, Hubendick (1951) used Lymnaea. For the purpose of this assessment, we follow the taxonomy used by NatureServe.

The Holotype of this species was collected together with Paratopotypes by Robert Miller and others in February 1976 from the Río (Potrero) Grande, about 9.6km W of the town of Ameca. Several Paratypes go back to collections from the type location in 1957 and 1971, one single male to a collection of R. Vrijenhoek and M. Douglas from a bridge over the Río Ameca (precisely: Río Cuisillos), 1km E of the estación Pacana, SE of the Presa La Vega, in 1981. No subpopulations are distinguished.
Ou and Yeo (1995) consider that Macrobrachium leptodactylus is a synonym of M. pilimanus.

The types Kingston used for her description of Skiffia francesae (1978) were collected by Miller and Fitzsimons in 1970 from the Río Teuchitlán E of Teuchitlán. Two decades later, in 2006, a stock of Skiffia was found in the Molino pond near Cuyacapán, Laguna de Sayula drainage. Fish from this locality are regarded to belong to the Golden Skiffia. According to these two drainages, two subpopulations are recognized: The Upper Río Ameca subpopulation (type subpopulation) and the Laguna de Sayula subpopulation. Both are regarded Extinct in the Wild.

Garman reported a single female collected by E. Palmer in the early 1890's from a spring or endorheic stream near Parras, Coahuila, but regarded it as Characodon lateralis. Jordan and Evermann, however, restricted lateralis to Central America following the designation given by Günther and renamed this individual from Parras Characodon garmani without examinating it. Meek again used the name Characodon garmani for individuals from the Mezquital river, too, as the name Characodon lateralis was occupied for fish from "lowland streams from Central America, north to the state of Jalisco". This directly led to Regan synonymizing both species as Characodon lateralis, as he couldn't find any difference between them (as, except for this single female, all fish came from the Mezquital drainage). Finally, it was Smith and Miller (1983) who re-examined the Holotype of garmani and accepted the species as valid.
This has been recognised as a subspecies of Elimia catonaria. But is in AFS list. A. Bogan comments that other subspecies are also present: E. pastelli (Lea, 1858).
There are taxonomic issues relating to identity of the species in the genus Bythinella, but these can only be resolved with live specimens, and this species has not been recorded for over 50 years.

Genetic studies suggest that this species should be regarded as a variant of the widespread Bromus secalinus L. (Ainouche and Bayer 1997), whilst Tourney (1968) earlier placed the taxon as a subspecies of Bromus grossus Desf. ex DC.

Seed protein, allozyme, and nuclear DNA sequence studies have shown a very close similarity to the widespread B. hordeaceus L., from which B. interruptus is believed to have originated through mutation (Rumsey and Stroh 2020). Cope and Gray (2009) regarded the species as a natural mutation of B. hordeaceus.

The first known collection of the species is from 1849 at Odsey, Cambridgeshire, UK (Rumsey and Stroh 2020). The species is considered a fodder crop wild relative (Maxted and Kell 2009, Hopkins and Maxted 2011).
Platytropius siamensis was described from the Chao Phraya River in Bangkok (Sauvage 1883) as a species of Pseudeutropius. Hora (1937) subsequently erected the genus Platytropius for this species.
The generic position is uncertain due to lack of anatomical data.

The genus Marstonia was formerly relegated to the synonomy of Pyrgulopsis by Hershler and Thompson (1987), but Thompson and Hershler (2002) later re-evaluated eastern North American species assigned to Pyrgulopsis and recognized them as distinct species of the genus Marstonia.

The genus Vanvoorstia contains three species. Vanvoorstia spectabilis and V. coccinea are common tropical (Indo-Pacific, including GBR) species, with the former also recorded from Lord Howe Island. While some confusion exists as to the exact differences between these two species (Price and Scott 1992), both are easily distinguished and considered very different from V. bennettiana, a very much smaller- and finer-meshed species in which the tetrasporangial stichidia are also easily defined.

There are now four species. Eric Coppejans (pers. comm.) indicates that there is a new species he described from East Africa which is probably Critically Endangered: Vanvoorstia incipiens De Clerck, Wynne & Coppejans (Phycologia 38 (1999): 394-400). This newly described species occurs massively in a single (rather small) bay along the east coast of Zanzibar, at about low tide level (large amounts drifting or entangled to other seaweeds in intertidal pools). Coppejans carried out over 200 collecting excursions along the Kenyan, Tanzanian (incl. Zanzibar) coast and NEVER found a single specimen anywhere else than the type locality, where we find it again year after year. It doesn't occur in the neighbouring bays, which look "identical" to this one! If that bay would be disturbed (harbour, oil pollution, etc.) the only known (type) locality would disappear and we would have a similar story there within the same genus!! Apparently some representatives do not succeed in colonizing larger areas!
Treated by some as a variety under A. splendens (Achyranthes splendens var. atollensis (H. St. John) Govaerts) see World Checklist of Seed Plants 1(1): 6. 1995.
Was previously included in T. simonis, but is valid as a separate species (N. Bogutskaya, pers. comm.).

The current spelling of the specific name is correct. Clarke's (1985) spelling change, Alasmidonta maccordi, was unjustified and constituted a recommendation only (Turgeon et al. 1998).

A list of synonyms for this species can be found on The MUSSEL project web site (Graf and Cummings 2011).
Díaz et al. (2002) described Gracilinanus ignitus as a new species. Voss et al. (2005) described a new genus, Cryptonanus, and transferred G. ignitus to this new genus.

Morphological analyses support the view that Lithobates fisheri represents a distinct species (Jennings et al. 1995). Subpopulations from central Arizona and western New Mexico previously attributed to L. chiricahuensis have been suggested to belong to species on the basis of mtDNA analysis (Hekkala et al. 2011), however, this claim is disputed and is currently not recognized (Herrman et al. 2021).
This species was previously included in the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).

This species was previously within the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005). There is some doubt as to the correctness of the locality data associated with the specimen and there might also be taxonomic problems with this species (J. Savage pers. comm.).
This species was previously included in the genus Eleutherodactylus (Crawford and Smith 2005).
The placement of Pantanodon is problematic. Based on the most recent studies, it should be placed under Poeciliidae (Parenti 1981, Ghedotti 2000) (J. Sparks pers. comm.)
Mangifera casturi Kosterm. belongs to Taxon Group two of Mango M. indica L.

Arachis rigonii Krapov. & W.C.Greg. is a tertiary wild relative of Peanut, A. hypogaea L., according to the Harlan and De Wet (1971) Gene Pool concept (USDA, Agricultural Research Service, National Plant Germplasm System 2020).

Contomastix charrua was described from a population referred to Cnemidophorus (now Contomastix) lacertoides on the basis of differences in coloration, structure of the hyoid apparatus and geological history of the cape (Cabrera and Carreira 2009). Borteiro et al. (2013) found no morphological differences between the two taxa and referred C. charrua to the synonymy of C. lacertoides. S. Carreira (pers. comm. 2016) indicates that ongoing research has identified additional differences that may warrant recognizing C. charrua as a separate species, and recommends retaining C. charrua as a valid species pending comparison with material from the C. lacertoides type locality, which was not done by Borteiro et al. (2013).
Recent taxonomic work by Liew Thorseng has shown that this species is part of the genus Plectostoma.

Giles (1937) stressed the close taxonomic relationship of this deer with R. duvaucelii, within which it was placed by Haltenorth (1963: 58), Groves (1982; tentatively) and Corbet and Hill (1992). It was considered a full species by Pocock (1943), who even assigned it to its own monotypic genus Thaocervus, and by Lekagul and McNeely (1977), Groves and Grubb (1987) and Pitra et al. (2004). Most sources during 1945 to 2015 placed the species in the genus Cervus.
This species is considered endemic to Java, and previous records of this  species from throughout the rest of Southeast Asia refer to other  species (Kottelat and Widjanarti 2005).

Molecular analyses have demonstrated that all shads endemic to the Aegean, Black and Caspian Sea basins, including Alosa vistonica, share close phylogenetic relationships (Geiger et al. 2014). Their taxonomy may therefore be revised in the future.

Michaelsen's contemporary, Ude (1905) thought his species Notoscolex unipapillatus may be the same as T. orthostichon but this was disputed by Blakemore (2012) and by current studies (Blakemore, unpublished).  Of note is that the revision based on types by Michaelsen (1917) did not mention this similarity and showed the male pores to be radically different, both to M. unipapillatus and to Lee’s (1962) revision of London specimens of “Megascolides orthostichon” that Blakemore (2014) showed was T. maorica (see Blakemore 2014 fig. 12 comparisons with Benham’s original figures).  Lee (1962) was seemingly unaware of Michaelsen’s (1917) revision and also missed his own (Lee 1959) review as another apparently significant difference is the spermathecal pores being segmental in T. maorica rather than intersegmental as in T. unipapillata.  For T. orthostichon the spermathecal pore location was given by Lee (1959) as in 7/8/9 the same as T. unipapillatus but – as already noted – Michaelsen (1917) found the male pores and markings, at least, to differ conclusively for these two taxa.

Hypogaeon orthostichon Schmarda (1861) was the first native earthworm formally described from Australasia.  It was collected from Maunga Rei / Mount Wellington in Auckland, New Zealand by Ludwig Karl Schmarda sometime over a five week period of his visit in 1854.
This species was reviewed by Benham (1905), Michaelsen (1917), Lee (1959) and Blakemore (2000, 2008, 2012) with new combination in Tokea by Blakemore (2014).
Although the description of Tokea orthostichon (Schmarda, 1861) was basic, and partly in Latin, it was standard orthodoxy for the time and quite adequate for this species that Schmarda collected at Maunga Rei / Mount Wellington in 1854 as part of a world tour.

While there is no doubt that Coregonus subpopulations from eastern and southern parts of the North Sea basin were largely extirpated during the 20th century, this taxon's systematic status has been a topic of disagreement among researchers since the mid-2000s.

It has traditionally been considered to be distributed throughout the region, and separated from congeners based on its elongated snout and anadromous life history (Hansen et al. 2008). This concept of the taxon continues to be referred to as the "North Sea Houting" in published literature, with a single extant indigenous subpopulation understood to inhabit the Vidå River in Denmark.

However, comparative morphological evidence suggests that it is an extinct potamodromous species formerly restricted to the southern North Sea basin. Under this concept, anadromous subpopulations from northern Germany and Denmark together correspond to the congeneric Maraena Whitefish (Coregonus maraena), which also occurs in the Baltic Sea basin (Freyhof and Schöter 2005).

Subsequent molecular analyses have concluded that the Vidå River subpopulation is genetically distinct from those located further north, but failed to rule out that extinct subpopulations from the southern North Sea represented a distinct taxon (Hansen et al. 2008, Jacobsen et al. 2012). Moreover, the Vidå River subpopulation does not appear to be conspecific with these former subpopulations (Mehner et al. 2018).

In the absence of a general consensus, the IUCN Red List currently follows the nomenclature provided by Fricke et al. (2024).

This taxon is currently regarded as valid for global Red List purposes, but was treated as a subpopulation of the Arctic charr, Salvelinus alpinus (Linnaeus 1758), for the most recent national assessment (Nunn et al. 2023).

The taxonomic status of Salvelinus subpopulations inhabiting the British Isles has not been definitively resolved since a series of endemic species were described between the mid-19th and early 20th centuries (Adams and Maitland 2007).

In the United Kingdom and Ireland, all of these taxa are treated as junior synonyms of the Arctic Charr, the name of which has been routinely applied to a widespread complex of polymorphic charr populations occurring throughout the Holarctic region (Jonsson and Jonsson 2001). However, there remains considerable uncertainty regarding the systematics of the genus across the majority of this range (Reist et al. 2013, Taylor 2016, Whiteley et al. 2019).

Members of this "Arctic Charr complex" exhibit bewildering subpopulation-scale ecological and morphological variability. When such divergence occurs within a single lake system, the different sympatric forms are often referred to as “morphs”, “morphotypes”, "ecomorphs" or "ecotypes" (Snorrason et al. 1994, Adams et al. 1998, Knudsen et al. 2006, Klemetsen 2010, Muir et al. 2016).

Some of these subpopulations and sympatric forms have over time been described as nominal species, including at least 15 from North America, around 30 from Europe and 12 from Siberia and the Far East. However, these taxa encompass only a small fraction of charr distribution and diversity, and there exist significant differences in opinion regarding which of them should be considered valid (Savvaitova 1995, Adams and Maitland 2007, Kottelat and Freyhof 2007, Klemetsen 2010, Whiteley et al. 2019).

With the above in mind, there is an emerging consensus that the striking genetic and phenotypic diversity exhibited by members of this genus cannot be adequately represented by a single accepted taxonomic system (Whiteley et al. 2019).

The Red List currently follows the nomenclature provided by Fricke et al. (2024), albeit a species-oriented conservation management approach is unlikely to prove appropriate for members of this genus (Barthelemy et al. 2023; also see 'Conservation').
This species was previously within the genus Hyla, then was moved to the resurrected genus Hypsiboas (Faivovich et al. 2005) and subsequently to the genus Boana (Dubois 2017).
Hemignathus lucidus, H. hanapepe and H. affinis (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as H. lucidus following AOU (1998 & supplements); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993).

This species (Delissea undulata) was known from two varieties: D. undulata var. undulata and D. u. var. argutidentata. The variety from Hawai'i Island was elevated to D. argutidentata and the variety from Maui was elevated to D. undulata.
This species is known from only two specimens, the holotype collected by E.A. Eastwood in November 1911, and another specimen collected by Vincent A. Wager in December 1928.

There has been confusion regarding the identity of this species in the past. Raw (1973) assigned specimens from the KwaZulu-Natal Midlands to Scelotes guentheri, but these specimens were later described as S. bourquini (Broadley 1994). Because S. guentheri is known from only a single specimen, its taxonomic status remains uncertain, although most authors consider it valid (e.g., FitzSimons 1943, Broadley 1994, Branch 1998). The differences between these species are minor (the presence of a slightly higher ventral scale count, a postnasal scale and the absence of preanal pores) prompting Raw (2021) to suggest that S. bourquini should be synonymised with S. guentheri. However, this conclusion was based on the examination of limited material and therefore requires further data to confirm the result.
This species was recognized as distinct from Atelopus cruciger by Lötters et al. (2004).
Aegolius gradyi (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was newly described from fossil remains by Olson (2012).

Previously placed in genus Polyborus, now shown to be invalid as type unidentifiable (Banks and Browning 1995, Banks and Dove 1992). Frequently treated as a subspecies of C. plancus. Initial DNA studies, however, suggested that present form was a distinct species (Sibley and Monroe 1990), and this view was supported by later molecular analysis (Dove and Banks 1999). Monotypic.
Hemignathus lucidus, H. hanapepe and H. affinis (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) were previously lumped as H. lucidus following AOU (1998 & supplements); Sibley & Monroe (1990, 1993).

Govenia floridana was initially identified as the more widespread tropical species Govenia utriculata when discovered in 1957. However, the Florida population differs from G. utriculata in that the sheaths are not inflated, it is nearly polygonal in cross section, the column is prominently winged, and the petals are spotted (Greenwood 1991). Based on these differences, Govenia floridana was established as a distinct species by Brown (2000).

taxonomicNotes: Formerly included within C. ecaudatus, the specific status was recognised by Travouillon et al. (2019).

Previously (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) placed in the genus Alopecoenas and before that in the genus Gallicolumba but transferred to Pampusana on the grounds of the latter’s priority (Bruce et al. 2016). Closely allied to P. sanctaecrucis and (especially) P. stairi, and more distantly so to the P. jobiensis group. Monotypic.
Sometimes placed in genus Gallirallus or Rallus. Monotypic.

The Java Stingaree is known only from the type specimen (ZMB 5301) housed at the Museum für Naturkunde, Berlin, Germany. Taxonomy of the species is resolved, except for its placement in the genus Urolophus which is provisional (Last et al. 2016). The species was originally placed in the genus Trygonoptera (Martens 1864). It is a unique species of stingaree, easily differentiated from any other ray in the Java region or nearby areas. Its geographic range does not overlap with the range of the Kai Stingaree (Urolophus kaianus) which is the only other Indonesian stingaree species and occurs in far eastern Indonesia (Last et al. 2016).
Some authors have suggested that this taxon may be a hybrid. However, it is currently accepted as a valid species.

The name Bos taurus was used by Carl Linnaeus in 1758 for feral cattle. The scientific name Bos primigenius was proposed for the Aurochs by Ludwig Bojanus in 1825 (later dated to 1827). The International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature (2003) placed Bos primigenius on the Official List of Specific Names in Zoology and thereby recognized the validity of this name for the wild species.

Three subspecies are recognised B. p. primigenius (Eurasia), B. p. mauritanicus (North Africa), B. p. namadicus (South Asian subcontinent) (Van Vuure 2005).

Archaeozoological and genetic data indicate that taurine cattle Bos taurus were first domesticated from local Aurochs (B. p. primigenius) in the Near East around 10,500 years ago and that a second domestication (of B. p. namadicus) took place about 1500 years later in India, giving rise to the zebu Bos indicus line (Bollongino et al. 2012; Park et al. 2015; Pitt et al. 2019).
Psephotellus pulcherrimus (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was previously placed in the genus Psephotus.

Columba thiriouxi (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) was newly described from subfossil records by Hume (2011).

Gallinula nesiotis and G. comeri (del Hoyo and Collar 2014) were previously lumped as G. nesiotis following Sibley and Monroe (1990, 1993) and Groenenburg et al. (2008, 2009), and before that had been treated as separate species by Collar and Stuart (1985).

Palaeornis wardi (Handbook of the Birds of the World and BirdLife International 2020) was previously listed as Psittacula wardi (del Hoyo et al. 2014). Braun et al. (2019) report the situation where the parrot genera Psittinus, Tanygnathus and Mascarinus nest genetically within Psittacula, meaning that either Psittacula replaces these latter three genera or it breaks down into monophyletic genera of their own. The latter course is preferred, building on Braun et al. (2016), where several genera were established or resurrected including Palaeornis for P. eupatria and P. wardi.
Foudia delloni (del Hoyo and Collar 2016) was described by Cheke and Hume (2008).
